			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><hr /></td>
			</tr>
			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">IN retrospect, when I created my Hibernian Bard, I did one thing that kinda came from EQ.
<br />

<br />
I saw that my character had Strength, at the expense of the back stats (as I call them), which means that sometimes there will be problems with other songs and issues, if not punishment. As an example, the Human Bard in EQ has no Agility, and that thing takes punishment fast, and I have never seen a level 60 Human Bard yet! More Wood Elves get there than the other 2 types of Bards.
<br />

<br />
What this meant, and I remember mentioning it to my roomate who started an account at the same time, was that I did not want to be a meat shield, so I made sure that I had points in those "back stats" to ensure that I am not a mana drain. Eventually this means that you are "averaging" out the stats, and for a Bard, that's probably good, since you can easily switch from a tanking Bard to a Healing Bard, or a Buff'ing Bard. 
<br />

<br />
The one thing that always worried me, is that these games change. What Mythic does today, will change tomorrow and the new areas and ideas and dungeons will require different needs from each class and this will affect the stats ... and I would imagine that keeping these even some, is a good way to go for now.
<br />

<br />
Unless, you really know that you want to be a tanking Bard, for example ... or a Healing Bard ... (so bizarre that Music is not the primary thing for a Bard!) ... but still, I would not be a mana/power drain player. The mana/power drain players usually get a lot of flack and dumped from groups rather quickly. At least this happens in EQ a lot.</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
		</table></td>
	</tr>
